<body class="ignore-math"><article class="exercise exercise-like"><div class="introduction"><p>On the other hand  we now know that <span class="process-math">\(\int\tan(x)\dx{x}=\ln(\sec(x)+c\)</span> and we can use this knowledge. Suppose we need to compute <span class="process-math">\(\int\frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{u}\)</span> or <span class="process-math">\(\int\frac{u}{1-u^2}\dx{u}\text{.}\)</span> The same substitution we used to transform these into the integral <span class="process-math">\(\int\tan(x)\dx{x}\)</span> will work in reverse.</p></div>
<article class="task exercise-like"><h4 class="heading"><span class="codenumber">(a)</span></h4>
<p>Use the substitution <span class="process-math">\(u=\tan(x)\)</span> to show that:</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int\frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{u} =
\ln\left(\sec\left(\inverse\tan(u)\right)\right)+c.
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p>Now use your Algebra and Trigonometry skills to show that <span class="process-math">\(\sec\left(\inverse\tan(u)\right) = \sqrt{1+u^2}\)</span> so that</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int\frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{u} =
\frac12\ln\left(1+u^2\right)+c\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div></article><article class="task exercise-like"><h4 class="heading"><span class="codenumber">(b)</span></h4>
<p>Use the substitution <span class="process-math">\(u=\sin(x)\)</span> to show that</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int\frac{u}{1-u^2}\dx{u}=
\ln\left(\sec\left(\inverse\sin(u)\right)\right)+c.
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p>Now use your Algebra and Trigonometry skills to show that <span class="process-math">\(\sec\left(\inverse\sin(u)\right) = \sqrt{1-u^2}\)</span> so that</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int\frac{u}{1-u^2}\dx{u} =
-\frac12\ln\left(1-u^2\right)+c\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div></article></article></body>
</html>
